Moral Dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the U.S. government represents a massive bailout of the creditors of these institutions, whose losses had continued to grow in the face of falling house prices.
Now that the government is fully backing Fannie's and Freddie's debts, American taxpayers will have to cover everything that is not covered by the insufficient financial resources of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in the most capitalist country in the world?
Do the esteemed principles of capitalism not include the idea that those who believed in the real estate bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Is it fair that innocent taxpayers now have to bear the consequences of their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral issues of the current financial crisis were clearly outlined.
But they are not.
Above all, it is unclear whether the bailout will actually cost U.S. taxpayers in the end. It may prevent further systemic effects that would force the financial sector and thus the global economy to its knees.
Only because systemic effects are difficult to quantify does not mean that they do not exist.
In addition, the bonds issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as being equipped with an implicit guarantee from the U.S. government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the absence of a government rescue could undermine confidence in government securities—and because they are associated with them—also in other financial instruments.
The problems extend far beyond the U.S. economy.
The global economy has been driven in recent years by remarkable speculative booms and crashes in asset values, bringing questions of trust as well as fairness into the equation.
Also in many other countries, similar booms in the housing sector are currently coming to an end, and they may be facing the same struggles—and the same moral dilemmas—as the U.S. economy is currently experiencing.
And the problem is not only the housing markets.
The stock markets are also facing this.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose by a factor of 5 between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose by a factor of 5 in real terms between 2003 and 2007 and has since lost a third of its value.
Similar booms and crashes in stock markets have occurred in many other countries.
As long as they continued, the preceding boom phases led to overheating of these economies.
Now that they have reversed, a loss of confidence could seize the global economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts may be necessary—not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust, no way to predict how people will react when, in the face of collapsing markets, help fails to arrive.
The reactions of people to these events depend on their emotions and their sense of justice.
The described booms and crashes have caused a significant redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested in the stock market or the housing market did well or poorly depending on the timing.
People will judge the fairness of these outcomes based on what they were told and the implicit promises they derived from it.
What was told to people in all these countries about the markets into which they invested their money?
Did everything really correspond to the truth?
Unfortunately, there is no way to find out.
Policy can only respond generally and cannot address each case individually.
We know that the economic growth of recent times has been spectacular in many countries.
But were the capital investments sold at too high a price in their markets?
Have cynical sellers here and elsewhere led people to believe that the boom times would bring prosperity for all?
It is certain that, although there may have been a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice with reservations – most of the losers in this game are not starving.
Yet we cannot casually conclude from this that all their losses should be left entirely untouched.
The persistent problem is one of "trust and belief."
National economies flourish only when "trust and belief" prevail.
The current situation, in which speculative booms have driven the global economy – and now, after their collapse, are driving it into recession – suggests that people who have promoted certain capital investments have done so against trust and belief.
Take the investors who held bonds issued by Fannie and Freddie.
Although the U.S. government never officially promised to come to their aid in times of need, it created a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to assess their strength in an annual report.
This agency has never even admitted that there was a housing bubble.
The top officials of the government never issued a warning.
Can we really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is beginning to discover the power of capitalism and its ability to transform national economies.
Yet capitalism relies on trust and belief.
A treatment perceived as unfair can be deadly for economic growth, because it means that people lose trust in companies and therefore are less willing to make their valuable capital and their labor force available to them.
Is such an outcome morally preferable to a bailout?
